The code violates the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) and can be refactored as follows:

1. Create separate interfaces for each notification type (email, SMS, push notifications, etc.) to avoid having a single interface with multiple responsibilities. For example:
```
interface EmailNotificationSender {
    void sendEmail(String recipient, String subject, String body);
}

interface SmsNotificationSender {
    void sendSMS(String phoneNumber, String message);
}

interface PushNotificationSender {
    void sendPushNotification(String deviceId, String title, String message);
}
```
2. Implement each interface in a separate class:
```
class EmailService implements EmailNotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void sendEmail(String recipient, String subject, String body) {
        System.out.println("Sending email to " + recipient + " with subject: " + subject);
    }
}

class SmsService implements SmsNotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void sendSMS(String phoneNumber, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending SMS to " + phoneNumber + ": " + message);
    }
}

class PushNotificationService implements PushNotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void sendPushNotification(String deviceId, String title, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending push notification to " + deviceId + " with title: " + title + " and message: " + message);
    }
}
```
3. Refactor the `EmailClient` class to use the new interfaces:
```
class EmailClient implements NotificationReceiver {
    @Override
    public void receiveNotification(String sender, String subject, String body) {
        System.out.println("Received email from " + sender + " with subject: " + subject);
    }
}
```
4. Refactor the `SMSClient` class to use the new interfaces:
```
class SmsClient implements NotificationReceiver {
    @Override
    public void receiveNotification(String sender, String message) {
        System.out.println("Received SMS from " + sender + ": " + message);
    }
}
```
5. Refactor the `PushNotificationClient` class to use the new interfaces:
```
class PushNotificationClient implements NotificationReceiver {
    @Override
    public void receiveNotification(String appId, String title, String message) {
        System.out.println("Received push notification from " + appId + " with title: " + title + " and message: " + message);
    }
}
```
By following these steps, the code will be more modular and easier to maintain, as each class will have a single responsibility and will only need to implement the interfaces that are relevant to it.

