The code violates the Open-Closed Principle (OCP) and the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).

The OCP states that a class should be open for extension but closed for modification. In this case, the `GameContext` class is modified when new characters are added or removed, which violates this principle. To fix this, we can create separate classes for each character and make them inherit from a common interface, such as `Character`. This way, the `GameContext` class will be closed for modification and open for extension.

The ISP states that a client should not be forced to depend on interfaces that it does not use. In this case, the `Character` interface has methods that are not used by all characters, such as `CastSpell()` and `Fly()`. To fix this, we can create separate interfaces for each character type, such as `Mage`, `Fighter`, and `Ranger`. This way, the client will only depend on the interfaces it actually uses.

